{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:34:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:34:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20647"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20647"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.04,0.83,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20647"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77977"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"9951"},{"type":"tags","id":"10955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11780"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32297"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe complement system is an important part of the innate immune system. It consists of more than 20 plasma proteins that are normally present in inactive forms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of complement activation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All pathways directly activate C5 convertase","The alternative pathway requires antibody binding","The lectin pathway directly activates the membrane attack complex","All pathways converge at the formation of C3 convertase","The classical pathway requires mannose-binding lectin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe complement system has three activation pathways that all converge at \u003Cstrong\u003Eall pathways converge at the formation of C3 convertase\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a critical step where C3 is cleaved into C3a and C3b, leading to downstream effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll pathways directly activate C5 convertase\u003C/strong\u003E - C5 convertase formation requires prior C3 convertase activity and C3b generation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe alternative pathway requires antibody binding\u003C/strong\u003E - The alternative pathway is activated by microbial surfaces without antibodies. Antibody binding initiates the classical pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe lectin pathway directly activates the membrane attack complex\u003C/strong\u003E - The lectin pathway must first form C3 convertase before membrane attack complex assembly can occur\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe classical pathway requires mannose-binding lectin\u003C/strong\u003E - The classical pathway uses C1q binding to antibodies, while mannose-binding lectin initiates the lectin pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter C3 convertase formation, the pathways proceed through C5 convertase to form the membrane attack complex. This system produces inflammation via anaphylatoxins (C3a, C4a, C5a), enhances phagocytosis through opsonisation (C3b, iC3b), and causes cell lysis via the membrane attack complex (C5b-C9).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The complement system consists of plasma proteins that function in host defence against microbes and in inflammatory reactions.","Complement activation occurs through three pathways: classical, alternative, and lectin pathways, all leading to formation of C3 convertase.","The three main functions of the complement system are inflammation, opsonisation/phagocytosis, and cell lysis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 90-92"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77977"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20647"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77977"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T20:50:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T20:51:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95003"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9951"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Complement system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10955"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":